# Writing clean and reproducible code

> â€œAny fool can write code that a computer can understand. Good programmers write code that humans can understand.â€  
> â€“ Martin Fowler

This motto may sound a bit silly, but it actually shows a great truth. The thing about programming is that, of course, we write code that will force the computer to perform certain operations for us, but thatâ€™s only part of the story. The code we write will be read by more than just the computer (or programming language interpreter).

There will always be a group of people who will also be interested in reading it andÂ **understanding**Â it. For example:

- your team members, working on the same analytical tasks
    
- your code reviewer (whether itâ€™s a teacher at university or a colleague in a corporation - they need to be sure that your code works in a meaningful way)
    
- your future self, who is likely to return to the same project in due course to develop the issue further
    
- â€¦ and many others who you canâ€™t even imagine might be interested in reading your code.
    

It turns out that a programming language, with its tedious approach to all the missing brackets or commas, is actually much less demanding of people when they read your code. It is also much more responsive - giving you warnings or even errors when something is wrong from its perspective. But when a human reads your code - that set of computer instructions needs to beÂ **formatted**Â in a way that makes it more accessible and understandable to the observer. Placing importance on how your codeÂ **looks**, not just whether itÂ **works**, can save a lot of frustration in the long run.

## What are the key benefits of writing clean code?

- Your code is readable and easy for collaborators to understand, making it much easier to work together on a joint project.
    
- Your code is much more efficient to maintain - it takes much less time to change things or update certain portions when you know exactly which part is responsible for which action and how all things are connected for smooth execution.
    
- Your code can be a source of your confidence - showing your code is something you will do very often. Well, it will be exactly the proof of your work as a data scientist, right? Making sure your code is clean and readable makes it a much more enjoyable experience. If someone asks you what a particular part of your code does - youâ€™ll know right off the bat. Much less awkwardness guaranteed ðŸ˜‰

## 1. Naming variables (and functions)

### 1.1. Meaning

> **Your names need to have a meaning.**

Whenever you create a variable or function, you must give it a name. This name is exactly what you (or other users of your code) will use to call the object from memory. This means that the name itself should give the user some meaning, or at least an expectation of what we can get from the object.

> A name should tell you why it exists, what it does, and how it is used. If a name requires a comment, then the name does not reveal its intent.â€  
> Clean Code

```
# BAD
a <- 7 # number of days of the week
```

I guarantee that in a few seconds after writing this you will completely forget what this variable was created for.

```
# GOOD
daysInWeek <- 7 
```

This is a much better approach. Whenever you see this variable in your script, you will know exactly what it represents. Much more pleasant to read, isnâ€™t it?

### 1.2. How to write a name

> **Keep your names in the same convention to promote clarity.**

There are many naming conventions what are used across programming languages. Some examples are:

- alllowercase
    
- period.separated
    
- underscore_separated
    
- lowerCamelCase
    
- UpperCamelCase
    

Usually in the language conventions where is a preferred way of naming variables and functions. In R there is no specific rule regarding that, so you can flexibility choose what suits you the most. The only rule is: if you use some convention â€“ stick to it.

Hadley Wickham created a tidyverseÂ [styling guide](https://style.tidyverse.org/syntax.html)Â where he proposes using underscore_separated convention for naming objects in R, and sticking to nouns for variable names and verbs for functions.Â [Here](https://journal.r-project.org/archive/2012-2/RJournal_2012-2_Baaaath.pdf)Â you can find an overview of the popularity of different naming conventions in R.

## 2. Writing functions

> **Function should do one thing and it should do it well.**

The usual recommendation for writing a function in any programming language is to keep it simple. Creating a function that does a lot of things and returns very complex output objects is usually difficult to test, suboptimal at execution time and difficult to understand when you look into its code.

Functions in R are written to make our coding experience better - storing code for tasks we perform repetitively in reusable function calls. A good recommendation for writing functions in a meaningful way is to break down the complex operations we do into minimal working portions and create smaller, easier-to-read functions that do it step by step. So rather than writing one function that transforms your data, calculates some statistics from it and then runs some model on top, rather create smaller functions for transformation, calculation and modelling. Then, if you want, you can combine them all together into one wrapper function that simply calls them one by one.

## 3. Spacing (and formatting)

> **To make things readable you need to remember about proper spacing and indentation.**

Try to think of your code as if you were writing any other text document. Your code script is in fact just text. The only difference is that instead of using standard words, you use commands and functions. So it is the language that is different, not the writing rules themselves.

When you write a sentence in English, certain rules apply. For example, you put spaces after commas, never before them. If youâ€™re writing something in parentheses (and sometimes you just need to say something extra right there) you never put a space after the parenthesis, but before the text you have inside, right?

See ,if you do somestrangeformatting In your_text ( itâ€™s so difficult to read ,isnâ€™t it ? )

The same goes with code ðŸ˜Š

In R (following afterÂ [tidyverse style guidelines](https://style.tidyverse.org/syntax.html)) we should keep up withÂ **the following rules**:

> **Always put a space after a comma, never before, just like in regular English.**

See the example here:

```
# Good
 x[, 1]

# Bad
x[,1]
x[ ,1]
x[ , 1]
```

> **Do not put spaces inside or outside parentheses for regular function calls.**

```
# Good
mean(x, na.rm = TRUE)

# Bad
mean (x, na.rm = TRUE)  
mean( x, na.rm = TRUE )
```

> **Place a space before and after () when used with if, for, or while.**

```
# Good
if (debug) {
  show(x)
}

# Bad
if(debug){
    show(x)
}
```

## 4. Language-specific conventions

When programming in R it is good to follow these rules:

> **Donâ€™t use the ; sign.**

We can see that you know how to use it, but just donâ€™t. Donâ€™t put ; at the end of a line, and donâ€™t use ; to put multiple commands on one line. Just put your commands in separate lines. This is much more readable and easier for future debugging.

> **Use <-, not =, for assignment.**

It is easy to mistake = for ==, and thatâ€™s something we donâ€™t want. If you are saving something to an object, please use the arrow in R. It is there, you can use it, it is clear that goes where. Itâ€™s just better. The = sign is reserved for changing the values of the parameters of the functions. Arrow for objects, = for parameters. This is the way.

```
# Good
x <- 5

# Bad
x = 5
```

> **When overriding the default values of function parameters â€“ use the full name of the argument. The only exception â€“ the data argument.**

When calling a function, usually you have two types of arguments â€“ first that supplies data to the function call, and then other arguments which control the details of computations. When calling a function typically we omit the name of the data argument (because they are used in almost all functions at the first place). Then if we modify the default parameters for the details of the computations â€“ we should use the full name of the argument.

```
# Good
mean(1:10, na.rm = TRUE)

# Bad
mean(x = 1:10, , FALSE)
mean(, TRUE, x = c(1:10, NA))
```

> **When writing a comment each line should start with the # symbol and a single space.**

> **Comments are there to provide additional clarity on your code and findings.**

We use comments to record findings or analysis decision. We can also use them to explain what the code is doing. This is recommended at the beginning of your coding journey. In the future you should try to convert your code to be clearer and easy to read by itself â€“ by adding meaningful names to variables and functions, by keeping your code simple and to the point. This is the goal. In the meantime, use comments to add additional clarity. If you discover that you have more comments than code, you may consider switching to R Markdown, which works perfectly for making easy to read reports which keep your comments and code together.

> **Tidyverse pipes are to signify the actions that you are doing and make your code even clearer and not messier.**

Pipes are used to signify the sequence of actions performed on one object, that can be read one by one as they are executed by R. When you use %>% symbol try to remember about these things. Firstly, pipe should always have a space before it, and should be followed by a new line.

```
# Good
iris %>%
  group_by(Species) %>%
  summarize_if(is.numeric, mean) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  gather(measure, value, -Species) %>%
  arrange(value)

# Bad
iris %>% group_by(Species) %>% summarize_all(mean) %>%
ungroup %>% gather(measure, value, -Species) %>%
arrange(value)
```

Secondly, if your code is too long to fit in one line, put some of it into the next line. It wonâ€™t disturb the code execution, but it will be much easier to read.

```
iris %>%
  group_by(Species) %>%
  summarise(
    Sepal.Length = mean(Sepal.Length),
    Sepal.Width = mean(Sepal.Width),
    Species = n_distinct(Species)
  )
```

Thirdly, even if you use a function call that has no arguments - put the brackets at the end.

```
# Good
x %>% 
  unique() %>%
  sort()

# Bad
x %>% 
  unique %>%
  sort
```

And finally, lookÂ [here](https://style.tidyverse.org/pipes.html)Â for detailed guidelines of pipe formatting

# Reproducibility â€“ code sharing struggle

Repeatability in coding is a great goal. Itâ€™s a goal to make your results repeatable on different computers and regardless of the number of code executions. So if you do your analysis and share your code with someone else, they should get exactly the same results as you.

How do you make sure your code will run just as flawlessly on your device as on your colleagueâ€™s device?

> **Omit the special/local letters in variable names**

R will work with this, but your colleagueâ€™s computer may struggle to read it. The safest option is to simply use Latin letters and English names to name your variables and functions.

> **Include all package imports at the beginning of the script**

> **Make sure you include the code for automatic installation of packages if they are missing on a particular device**

You can use require() for that.

```
if (!require('ggplot2')) install.packages('ggplot2'); library('ggplot2')
```

Or utilize pacman:: package that will do it for you.

```
if (!require("pacman")) install.packages("pacman")
pacman::p_load(package1, package2, package_n)
```

More solutionsÂ [here](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/4090169/elegant-way-to-check-for-missing-packages-and-install-them)

> **Function set.seed() is your friend**

When creating random values or performing any calculations that rely on simulations (such as machine learning models), you need to put extra care into getting repeatable results. Here, setting the starting point for the pseudorandom number generator is a key point. Make sure you use the set.seed() function to get stable results across repetitions.

> **Never use absolute paths to your files**

Just make sure you set the working directory at the start of your script and use relative paths after that. This promotes transparency in your code and makes it resistant to file location changes.
